    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What does glutamine do for your body?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'L-Glutamine is the most abundant amino acid in the human body, comprising approximately 60% of the free amino acid pool in skeletal muscle. It serves as the primary fuel source for intestinal epithelial cells (enterocytes) that maintain gut barrier integrity, supports immune cell function (lymphocytes and macrophages rely on glutamine for energy), aids muscle recovery after intense exercise by replenishing depleted intramuscular glutamine stores, and plays a role in nitrogen transport between tissues. During intense exercise or physical stress, glutamine demand can exceed the body\'s ability to produce it, making it conditionally essential.' },
