    <h2 id="why-glutamine">Why Glutamine Is Essential for Gut Health and Recovery</h2>

    <p>L-Glutamine is the most abundant free amino acid in the human body, comprising approximately 60% of the amino acid pool in skeletal muscle and serving as the primary fuel source for two of your body's most demanding systems: the intestinal lining and the immune system. While your body can produce glutamine endogenously, intense exercise, physical stress, illness, and surgery can deplete glutamine stores faster than the body can replenish them — making glutamine "conditionally essential" during these periods of high demand.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">60%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of the free amino acid pool in skeletal muscle is glutamine. During intense exercise, <strong>intramuscular glutamine levels can drop by 30-50%</strong>, impairing muscle recovery, gut barrier integrity, and immune function simultaneously. Replenishing glutamine post-exercise accelerates recovery across all three systems.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The gut health connection is particularly significant. The cells lining your intestinal wall (enterocytes) consume more glutamine than any other cell type in the body. When glutamine is depleted — from exercise, stress, or poor nutrition — intestinal tight junctions weaken, allowing bacteria, toxins, and undigested food particles to pass through the gut wall into the bloodstream. This condition, known as increased intestinal permeability or "leaky gut," is linked to systemic inflammation, food sensitivities, autoimmune responses, and impaired nutrient absorption. Glutamine supplementation directly fuels enterocyte repair and strengthens tight junctions.</p>

