        <strong>Gut Barrier Integrity</strong>
        <p>Glutamine is the primary fuel for enterocytes — the cells forming the intestinal wall. It strengthens tight junctions between cells, reducing intestinal permeability and protecting against "leaky gut." A 2017 RCT showed 5g glutamine three times daily significantly improved gut barrier function.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Muscle Recovery</strong>
        <p>Intense exercise depletes intramuscular glutamine by 30-50%. Replenishing glutamine post-workout supports muscle protein synthesis, reduces DOMS severity, and accelerates recovery between training sessions. Most effective when combined with BCAAs and complete protein.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Immune Defense</strong>
        <p>Lymphocytes and macrophages use glutamine as their primary fuel. Depleted glutamine impairs immune surveillance, increasing upper respiratory infection risk by 40% in athletes during heavy training. Hospital ICUs use glutamine IV to support critically ill patients' immunity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <strong>Nitrogen Transport</strong>
        <p>Glutamine is the primary vehicle for transporting nitrogen between tissues, supporting protein synthesis throughout the body. It also serves as a precursor for glutamate — the brain's most abundant excitatory neurotransmitter — linking gut health to cognitive function.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

