    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Glutamine Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What does glutamine do for your body?</summary>
      <p>L-Glutamine is the most abundant amino acid in skeletal muscle (60% of the free amino acid pool). It fuels intestinal cells to maintain gut barrier integrity, supports immune cell function, aids muscle recovery, and transports nitrogen between tissues. During intense exercise, it becomes conditionally essential.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much glutamine should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies use 5-20g daily. Gummies provide 1-3g per serving, which is supplemental to dietary glutamine from protein-rich foods. For gut health, 5-10g daily is most studied. For recovery, 10-20g daily. Combine gummies with dietary sources for optimal intake.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is glutamine good for leaky gut?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Glutamine is the primary fuel for enterocytes that maintain the intestinal barrier. Research confirms it strengthens tight junctions, reducing intestinal permeability. A 2017 RCT found 5g glutamine three times daily significantly improved gut barrier function in IBS patients.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can glutamine help with immune function?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Glutamine fuels lymphocytes and macrophages. During intense exercise, blood glutamine drops 20-30%, impairing immunity. A meta-analysis found glutamine reduced infections in athletes by 40%. It is standard protocol in hospital ICUs for critically ill patients.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take glutamine gummies?</summary>
      <p>For gut health: morning on an empty stomach. For recovery: within 30 minutes after exercise. For immune support: split between morning and evening. Consistency of daily intake matters more than perfect timing.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are glutamine gummies safe?</summary>
      <p>L-Glutamine is very safe, with no adverse effects at doses up to 40g/day in studies. Gummy doses (1-3g) are well within safe limits. Avoid if you have liver disease or hepatic encephalopathy. Cancer patients should consult their oncologist. Kidney disease patients should check with their physician.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between L-glutamine and glutamine?</summary>
      <p>L-Glutamine is the biologically active form your body uses. D-Glutamine is biologically inactive. When labels say "glutamine," it is almost always L-Glutamine. Look for "L-Glutamine" on the supplement facts panel for certainty. All products in our evaluation use L-Glutamine.</p>
    </details>

